z= \cos(x) + i\sin(x),
\frac{1}{1+z}= 1 + i\tan(x/2)
z=\cos x+i\sin x=e^{ix}
\tan(x/2)=\frac{e^{ix/2}-e^{-ix/2}}{i(e^{ix/2}+e^{-ix/2})}=\frac{e^{ix}-1}{i(e^{ix}+1)}=\frac{z-1}{i(z+1)}
i\tan(x/2)=i\frac{z-1}{i(z+1)}=\frac{z-1}{z+1}=1-\frac{2}{z+1}
\frac1{1+z}=\frac12(1-i\tan(x/2))
x=\pi/2
\cos\frac\pi2 = 0
\sin\frac\pi2 = 1
z=0 + i\cdot 1 = i
\frac{1}{1+z} = \frac{1}{1+i}=\frac{1-i}{(1+i)(1-i)}=\frac{1-i}{2},
\tan\frac{x}{2} = \tan\frac{\pi}{4} = 1
1+i\tan\left(\frac x2\right) = 1+i
